DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The parity principle, introduced by Clark and Chalmers (1998), holds that if an external process plays the same functional role as an internal one, it should count as cognitive. This domain encompasses the principle's formulation, major philosophical critiques, and proposed alternatives. The central debate revolves around whether functional parity is sufficient for cognitive status or whether additional criteria are needed.

Critics like Adams and Aizawa (2001) argue that parity leads to "cognitive bloat" and that genuine cognition requires non-derived content. Rupert (2004, 2009) challenges the principle via his Hypothesis of Embedded Cognition (HEC), proposing that cognitive systems are individuated by causal integration rather than parity. Sprevak (2009) and Wheeler (2010) explore whether functionalism entails extended mind, while Wheeler (2011) seeks conceptual clarification of what parity actually requires.

Recent work proposes alternatives to parity: Candiotto (2022) advances the "not possible without" principle emphasizing existential necessity; Goldstone (2019) introduces a "Reversed Parity Principle" for internal tool-building; Oliveira (2025) adds "maintainability" to trust-and-glue criteria. Smithies (2018) argues that epistemological accessibilism is incompatible with vehicle externalism, challenging parity from an epistemic angle.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain directly addresses the methodological foundations of extended mind theory. Understanding parity critiques illuminates why cognitive offloading cases may or may not constitute genuine cognitive extension. The debate over cognitive criteria shapes how we conceptualize the boundaries between cognitive processes and mere coupling.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Few papers systematically compare parity with alternative principles across multiple case studies. Limited empirical testing of whether parity matches folk intuitions about cognition (though see experimental philosophy work by Y\u00fcksel 2025). Underdeveloped connection between parity debates and recent work on cognitive integration (Heersmink, Kirchhoff).

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Structure synthesis around three positions: (1) pro-parity defenses (Wheeler, Clark), (2) anti-parity critiques demanding additional cognitive criteria (Adams & Aizawa, Rupert, Sprevak), (3) alternative principles that transcend or replace parity (Candiotto, Goldstone). Highlight how the debate shifted from whether parity is correct to what cognitive criteria should replace or supplement it.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Pro-Parity Functionalists: 2 papers - Defend functional parity as sufficient or necessary for cognitive status
- Anti-Parity Internalists: 6 papers - Argue parity is insufficient; demand mark of the cognitive, natural kinds, or other criteria
- Alternative Principles: 3 papers - Propose replacements for or supplements to parity
- Epistemological Critiques: 1 paper - Challenge parity on grounds of epistemic access
- Recent Applications: 4 papers - Apply parity debates to AI, privacy, consciousness
