  RELEVANCE: The RPP provides a novel perspective on parity by reversing its direction. Rather than asking whether external tools can be cognitive, Goldstone asks what parity reasoning reveals about internal cognitive structures. This matters for cognitive offloading: it suggests that internal and external tools may be more symmetrically related than traditional debates assume, challenging both internalist and externalist orthodoxies.

